The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion
		 Friday, June 18, 2004  Paperback Pickings				 																Peek into lifes dark alleyThe kite runner (Bloomsbury,  6.99) by Khaled Hosseini is mostly set in Seventies Afghanistan, and tells the story of 12-year-old Amir, who is desperate to win the approval of his father and is determined to win the local kite-fighting tournament to prove that he has the makings of a man. His loyal friend, Hassan, promises to help him, in spite of being a lowly servant jeered at in the street. Amir feels secretly jealous of Hassans courage and the place he holds in his fathers heart. But the Russians invade, and Amirs family is forced to flee to America. But Amir resolves to return one day, to seek out what he understands to be redemption. I became what I am today at the age of twelve, on a frigid overcast day in the winter of 1975. I remember the precise moment, crouching behind a crumbling wall, peeking into the alley near the frozen creek...Looking back now, I realize I have been peeking into that deserted alley for the last twenty-six years.Speak right for a call centre job! (Penguin, Rs 250) by Arjun Raina is a complete training guide to developing English-speaking skills for the international call-centre industry (also referred to as the telephonic interface). It trains tele-agents to be clear, prompt and precise with their responses, and to speak the language correctly, pleasantly and intelligibly. It also provides advice on coping with changes of lifestyle in a call centre, and a list of leading Indian call centres.Wormwood (Faber,  3.25) by G.P. Taylor sets its sights at the farthest depths of space, but has its feet planted in Londons Bloomsbury Square. The time is 1756. Dr Sabian Blake  astronomer, scientist and master of the Cabala  is in possession of the Nemorensis, an ancient leather-bound volume that holds the secrets of the universe. Scribbled into one of its margins is a mysterious prophecy, and deciphering it could prove the key to saving London from a catastrophic fate. This is a tale of sorcery, intrigue and supernatural strife by a writer who has spent his whole life searching for the secrets of the universe, and lives in a secluded graveyard.Brahmins and bungalows: Travels through South Indian History (Penguin, Rs 295) by Kavita Watsa is a lovingly written memoir-cum-travelogue, which depicts a deeply cosmopolitan land south of the Vindhyas. Watsa presents a rich blend of landscapes and architecture  Goa, Hampi, Bangalore, Pondi- cherry, Tranquebar, and the woods of Kodaikanal.
